w such attempts to link black music and dance to Africa unintentionally reinforced the binary relationships between the West and Africa, white and black, the modern and the primitive, science and magic, and rural and urban. It was, Garcia demonstrates, modernity's determinations of unraced, heteronormative, and productive bodies, and of scientific truth that helped defer the realization of individual and political freedom in the world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 7aMUSIC / Ethnomusicology.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311069634940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478093251?locatt=mode:legacyzOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478093251zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478093251/original  a978-3-11-069634-9 Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA